      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing, let's dive into the world of mitosis, where the magic of cell division happens. Imagine a goblin village, where each goblin represents a cell. The goblins are preparing for a grand festival, and they need to split into two equally skilled teams. Here's how the goblins go about it:\n\n1. **Prophase**: The goblins gather in the village square, and their leader, the Grand Goblin, announces the festival. The goblins start to prepare their costumes and tools. In the cell, the chromosomes condense and become visible, and the nuclear envelope starts to break down.\n\n2. **Metaphase**: The goblins line up in the village square, perfectly aligned along the central path. In the cell, the chromosomes line up along the metaphase plate, an imaginary line in the middle of the cell.\n\n3. **Anaphase**: The Grand Goblin signals the start of the splitting. The goblins on one side of the line start to move towards the opposite side, while the goblins on the other side do the same. In the cell, the sister chromatids are pulled apart by the spindle fibers and move to opposite poles.\n\n4. **Telophase**",
