      "content": "Yes, that's correct! Cytokinesis is the process where the cell's cytoplasm divides, resulting in two separate daughter cells, each with its own nucleus and identical set of chromosomes. It's the physical splitting of the cell that follows the completion of mitosis.\n\nFor a test, it's important to remember that cytokinesis is the final step in cell division, ensuring that each daughter cell receives an equal and complete set of chromosomes. The key points to remember are:\n\n1. Cytokinesis begins during Telophase, after the chromosomes have been separated and the nuclear envelopes have reformed.\n2. The cell membrane pinches inwards at the equator of the cell, a process known as cleavage, eventually leading to the formation of two separate cells.\n3. In animal cells, this is facilitated by a structure called the contractile ring, which constricts to divide the cell in two.\n4. In plant cells, a cell plate forms along the equator, eventually developing into a separating wall between the two new cells.\n\nUnderstanding these steps will help you grasp the overall process of cell division and the importance of cytokinesis in ensuring that each daughter cell is a complete and functional unit.",
